order-top-color:#f0f0f0;height:15pt;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:x-small;"&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.gadgetell.com/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;font color="#0066cc"&gt;Gadgetell&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt; &lt;tr style="height:15pt;"&gt; &lt;td class="style5" style="border-right:windowtext 0.5pt solid;border-bottom-color:#f0f0f0;border-left:windowtext 0.5pt solid;width:118pt;border-top-color:#f0f0f0;height:15pt;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:x-small;"&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.liliputing.com/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;font color="#0066cc"&gt;Liliputing&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;img src="http://windowsconnected.com/aggbug.aspx?PostID=27993" width="1" height="1"&gt;</description><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/Microsoft/default.aspx">Microsoft</category><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/HP/default.aspx">HP</category><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/HPMagicGiveaway/default.aspx">HPMagicGiveaway</category><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/HPMagic/default.aspx">HPMagic</category></item><item><title>Apple Apologists Go Too Far…..</title><link>http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/matt/archive/2008/12/09/apple-apologists-go-too-far.aspx</link><pubDate>Tue, 09 Dec 2008 18:04:43 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">6a8e43d9-c7d6-4571-afe6-bea9fc913020:27953</guid><dc:creator>Matt Freestone</dc:creator><slash:comments>11</slash:comments><description>&lt;p&gt;So, let’s start out with the link that has prompted me to write this article;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;a title="http://gizmodo.com/5101110/apple-no-reasonable-person-should-trust-their-marketing" href="http://gizmodo.com/5101110/apple-no-reasonable-person-should-trust-their-marketing"&gt;http://gizmodo.com/5101110/apple-no-reasonable-person-should-trust-their-marketing&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Now, essentially the point of this article is that Apple admits to lying about the ‘twice the speed, half the price’ claims on the iPhone 3G marketing.&amp;#160; Below is from the Gizmodo article;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;After a legal complaint by 70-year-old William Gillis over the &amp;quot;twice as fast for half the price&amp;quot; statement found in iPhone 3G marketing, Apple responded with a 9-page, 32-point rebuttal—one paragraph of which included this overly harsh, but very telling, statement: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Plaintiff&amp;#39;s claims, and those of the purported class, are barred by the fact that the alleged deceptive statements were such that no reasonable person in Plaintiff&amp;#39;s position could have reasonably relied on or misunderstood Apple&amp;#39;s statements as claims of fact.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;strong&gt;In other words, if you believe what Apple says in an Apple ad, you are not a reasonable person. Well that point is more clear by the moment, isn&amp;#39;t it?&lt;/strong&gt;   &lt;p&gt;This reminds me of the Apple ads years ago on their ‘fastest computers in the world’ marketing campaign.&amp;#160; Remember these?&amp;#160; Apple was forced to release their testing data and I read the data.&amp;#160; When they performed their tests they disabled all the advanced features on the Intel processors for the test including hyper-threading, cache, etc.&amp;#160; In fact, the UK seems to keep a close eye on Apple (thankfully at least someone does) and tries to stop them when they lie.&amp;#160; See the below links I just found Google’ing ‘apple faster computers in the world ads.’&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://news.cnet.com/2100-1042_3-5180251.html"&gt;Apple told to halt ‘world’s fastest PC’ claims&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/3797261.stm"&gt;Apple Power Mac ads misleading&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;And, it seems, the United Kingdom is again stopping Apple from lying to the public in their advertising;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.pcworld.com/article/154558/apple_really_fast_iphone_ad_banned_in_uk.html"&gt;Apple ‘Really Fast’ iPhone Ad Banned in the UK&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;So, since everyone else covered this I wasn’t planning on writing about it until I started reading the comments posted to the Gizmodo article.&amp;#160; I have quoted some below with comments from me;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;“LMFAO :)      &lt;br /&gt;you took it out of context ,however, i think you&amp;#39;d be lying to yourself if you believe anybody&amp;#39;s ads altogether, so please dont apple out to be the bad guy. “&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;So it’s ok to lie, everyone does it right?&amp;#160; Besides, you took the blatant admitting of a lie out of context..?????&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;“Sorry Gizmodo, you FAIL on this one.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;That is pure boilerplate language consistently used in any dispute of this nature. It is a simple rebuttal that is near automatically included. And, generally, in advertising, it is true to a fairly consistent degree.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;So, yah, FAIL! “&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Pure boilerplate language?&amp;#160; Really?&amp;#160; To say that your customers are too stupid to see a lie and therefore shouldn’t be taken seriously is boiler plate language? I highly doubt it.&amp;#160; If it was boiler plate then I think that language would have been used in the ‘Vista capable’ lawsuit, and if it had would be front page news for days.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;“Since when did we start believing ANYTHING from ANY advertisement?”&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Again, it’s ok to lie and deceive consumers…… If you’re Apple anyhow.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;“For the first time in my life I want to punch a 70 year old man in the face.”&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Really?&amp;#160; So, because this poor guy got ripped off and decided to do something about it he deserves violence to be wrought upon him?&amp;#160; Seriously?&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;And trust me, the list goes on.&amp;#160; Many of the comments I wouldn’t repost here due to vulgarity.&amp;#160; Feel free to look at the link and read through the comments yourself.&amp;#160; The sheer hate and irrational justification of people who seem to have joined the non-existent Apple cult religion continues to astound me.&amp;#160; Don’t misunderstand me.&amp;#160; I do not think that Apple condones this type of behavior, nor do I think that all ‘Apple fans’ behave this way.&amp;#160; This is mere commentary about people who DO behave this way, AND that I believe this type of reaction emboldens Apple to continue their false advertising.&amp;#160; With this kind of support, why would they stop their false advertising?&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Basically all I have to say is, come on guys, seriously?&amp;#160; You really want to defend false advertising just because it’s your beloved Apple who can do no wrong?&amp;#160; You really want to react irrationally and angrily at people that dare challenge the almighty Apple?&amp;#160; I’m sure I’ll see my own share of this in response to this article just as I did to my &lt;a href="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/matt/archive/2008/04/29/the-vista-schoolyard-bullies.aspx"&gt;“Vista Schoolyard Bullies”&lt;/a&gt; post.&amp;#160; All I have to say is maybe you should watch &lt;a href="http://www.techradar.com/news/computing/the-simpsons-mapple-store-opens-in-springfield-489525"&gt;The Simpsons “Mapple”&lt;/a&gt; episode and take a hard long look at yourself…… Besides, it’s really funny.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;p&gt;So, what do you think?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;img src="http://windowsconnected.com/aggbug.aspx?PostID=27953" width="1" height="1"&gt;</description></item><item><title>Windows 7 RTM in April?, My Prediction Summer 2009</title><link>http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/2008/12/09/windows-7-rtm-in-april-my-prediction-summer-2009.aspx</link><pubDate>Tue, 09 Dec 2008 17:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">6a8e43d9-c7d6-4571-afe6-bea9fc913020:27957</guid><dc:creator>Josh Phillips</dc:creator><slash:comments>3</slash:comments><description>&lt;p&gt;Paul (&lt;a target="_blank" href="http://community.winsupersite.com/blogs/paul/archive/2008/12/05/when-will-windows-7-ship-my-prediction-april-2009.aspx"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;)&amp;nbsp;is expecting Windows 7 to be finalized by April, at the latest.&amp;nbsp; My personal opinion is that date would be very hard to hit. I put my money on this coming summer.&amp;nbsp; Here is why.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We are about to come up on the holidays and if the rumors of getting Beta1 out by early January are to be believed then they will need to have Beta1 DONE by next week.&amp;nbsp; Why? Like all major corporations their employees will all be on holiday/vacation from mid December until well after the first of the year.&amp;nbsp; Likely after CES.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So lets assume they hit Beta 1 before the end of year and vendors galore are showing it off at CES.&amp;nbsp; The world is a beautiful place and everyone is happy.&amp;nbsp; You will ramp up the Beta testing starting mid-Jan to early Feb. Initially you start out with any private testers. Then your Technet and MSDN subscribers. Then expand it again to a mostly public release where people can file bug online.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now once you have the Beta out the whole time you are fixing bugs behind the scenes, but you also have to allow time for bug fixes that you have not come across yet in your testing.&amp;nbsp; This takes you into late March early April as you triage and fix these and incorporate them into the builds.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now in order to test these fixes that you put in you will have to send out one more release to tester, probably called a Release Candidate. This will be a quicker turn around, but I think still takes you into the summer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So my prediction is that we will see Windows 7 this coming Summer.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;img src="http://windowsconnected.com/aggbug.aspx?PostID=27957" width="1" height="1"&gt;</description><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/Windows+7/default.aspx">Windows 7</category></item><item><title>HP Magic Giveaway Rolls On</title><link>http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/2008/12/08/hp-magic-giveaway-rolls-on.aspx</link><pubDate>Mon, 08 Dec 2008 18:14:53 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">6a8e43d9-c7d6-4571-afe6-bea9fc913020:27942</guid><dc:creator>Josh Phillips</dc:creator><slash:comments>0</slash:comments><description>&lt;p&gt;The HP Magic Giveaways aren&amp;#39;t even half over yet and new ones open each day so keep up to date on each site as they will all have their own set of rules. Over 60,000 dollars in equipment &amp;amp; software have been awarded and a whole more is still to be awarded.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Here is a list of currently active contest:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;table class="style6" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"&gt;  &lt;tr style="height:15pt;"&gt; &lt;td style="border-bottom-color:#f0f0f0;border-left:windowtext 0.5pt solid;background-color:#eeece1;border-top-color:#f0f0f0;width:118pt;height:15pt;border-right:windowtext 0.5pt solid;" class="xl73"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:x-small;"&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.dtemama.com/" target="_blank"&gt;Down-to-Earth Mama&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt; &lt;td style="border-bottom-color:#f0f0f0;border-left:windowtext 0.5pt solid;background-color:#eeece1;border-top-color:#f0f0f0;border-right:windowtext 0.5pt solid;" class="xl77" rowspan="4"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:x-small;"&gt;03-Dec&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt; &lt;td style="border-bottom-color:#f0f0f0;background-color:#eeece1;border-top-color:#f0f0f0;border-left-color:#f0f0f0;border-right:windowtext 0.5pt solid;" class="xl68" rowspan="4"&gt;&lt;span style="fo