;#39;sans-serif&amp;#39;;font-size:10pt;"&gt;May require restart&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt; &lt;td style="padding-bottom:0.75pt;padding-left:0.75pt;padding-right:0.75pt;background:#e9e9e6;height:31.5pt;padding-top:0.75pt;"&gt; &lt;p class="MsoNormal"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:&amp;#39;Verdana&amp;#39;,&amp;#39;sans-serif&amp;#39;;font-size:10pt;"&gt;Microsoft Windows&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;img src="http://windowsconnected.com/aggbug.aspx?PostID=27838" width="1" height="1"&gt;</description><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/security/default.aspx">security</category></item><item><title>Windows 7 - Mobile Broadband</title><link>http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/2008/12/04/windows-7-mobile-broadband.aspx</link><pubDate>Thu, 04 Dec 2008 18:29:27 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">6a8e43d9-c7d6-4571-afe6-bea9fc913020:27836</guid><dc:creator>Josh Phillips</dc:creator><slash:comments>0</slash:comments><description>&lt;p&gt;One of the &lt;a href="http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/press/2008/nov08/11-05WinHECPR.mspx" target="_blank"&gt;Windows 7 features&lt;/a&gt; that I most looking forward to is &lt;a href="http://download.microsoft.com/download/5/E/6/5E66B27B-988B-4F50-AF3A-C2FF1E62180F/MBL-T603_WH08.pptx" target="_blank"&gt;Mobile Broadband&lt;/a&gt;. This feature will allow users the ability to connect via a cellular modem limiting the need for a connection manager. Separating the driver from the connection manager should makes mobile broadband more accessible to the general public who, for very good reason, get frustrated with the complexity today.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://windowsconnected.com/cfs-file.ashx/__key/CommunityServer.Blogs.Components.WeblogFiles/joshs_5F00_blog/image_5F00_2.png"&gt;&lt;img style="border-bottom:0px;border-left:0px;border-top:0px;border-right:0px;" border="0" alt="image" src="http://windowsconnected.com/cfs-file.ashx/__key/CommunityServer.Blogs.Components.WeblogFiles/joshs_5F00_blog/image_5F00_thumb.png" width="421" height="303" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Both &lt;a href="http://www.option.com/news/detail05.cfm?newsitemgroup_id=708" target="_blank"&gt;Option&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="http://www.webwire.com/ViewPressRel.asp?aId=79264" target="_blank"&gt;Sierra&lt;/a&gt; have already announced &lt;a href="http://download.microsoft.com/download/5/E/6/5E66B27B-988B-4F50-AF3A-C2FF1E62180F/MBL-T602_WH08.pptx" target="_blank"&gt;driver support for Windows 7 Mobile broadband&lt;/a&gt; which means that many of the devices used by the current US carries will be covered.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://windowsconnected.com/cfs-file.ashx/__key/CommunityServer.Blogs.Components.WeblogFiles/joshs_5F00_blog/image_5F00_4.png"&gt;&lt;img style="border-bottom:0px;border-left:0px;border-top:0px;border-right:0px;" border="0" alt="image" src="http://windowsconnected.com/cfs-file.ashx/__key/CommunityServer.Blogs.Components.WeblogFiles/joshs_5F00_blog/image_5F00_thumb_5F00_1.png" width="263" height="180" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://windowsconnected.com/cfs-file.ashx/__key/CommunityServer.Blogs.Components.WeblogFiles/joshs_5F00_blog/image_5F00_6.png"&gt;&lt;img style="border-bottom:0px;border-left:0px;border-top:0px;border-right:0px;" border="0" alt="image" src="http://windowsconnected.com/cfs-file.ashx/__key/CommunityServer.Blogs.Components.WeblogFiles/joshs_5F00_blog/image_5F00_thumb_5F00_2.png" width="244" height="180" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It sounds like a simple thing, but I remember needing a wireless connection manager for connecting to wireless access points now I couldn&amp;#39;t imagine using one. My hope is that Windows 7 makes cellular as easy and as accessible as wireless has become.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;img src="http://windowsconnected.com/aggbug.aspx?PostID=27836" width="1" height="1"&gt;</description><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/Windows+7/default.aspx">Windows 7</category><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/wwan/default.aspx">wwan</category><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/mobile+broadband/default.aspx">mobile broadband</category></item><item><title>Windows Live Home Thoughts</title><link>http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/2008/12/04/windows-live-home-thoughts.aspx</link><pubDate>Thu, 04 Dec 2008 16:42:49 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">6a8e43d9-c7d6-4571-afe6-bea9fc913020:27825</guid><dc:creator>Josh Phillips</dc:creator><slash:comments>6</slash:comments><description>&lt;p&gt;The Windows &lt;a href="http://blogs.zdnet.com/microsoft/?p=1744" target="_blank"&gt;Live Wave 3 services began rolling out this week&lt;/a&gt; and seem to be having some growing pains. The main portal for Windows Live is &lt;a href="http://home.live.com" target="_blank"&gt;home.live.com&lt;/a&gt; which has added various social networking aspects where people can join your &amp;quot;network&amp;quot;, add you to &amp;quot;groups&amp;quot;, etc .&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Adding people to your network is easy and even lets you import from Linked-In, Facebook, and Windows Live.&amp;nbsp; The down side is that the service assumes that if you add someone to your &amp;quot;network&amp;quot; that you also want to add them to your Windows Messenger contact...which is not necessarily the case.&amp;nbsp; For many these are maintained separately on purpose and someone like a Scoble really wouldn&amp;#39;t want all the people that he added chatting with him via IM.&amp;nbsp; They should enhance the contacts list such that Messenger contacts are maintained separately or have a separate flag on each person in your network if they are to show up in your messenger list.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;img style="border-bottom:0px;border-left:0px;border-top:0px;border-right:0px;" border="0" alt="Home-1" src="http://windowsconnected.com/cfs-file.ashx/__key/CommunityServer.Blogs.Components.WeblogFiles/joshs_5F00_blog/Home_2D00_1_5F00_3.png" width="611" height="224" /&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The &amp;quot;What&amp;#39;s New&amp;quot; feed is like what you might get via twitter or Facebook and even has the ability to web activities via&amp;nbsp; twitter &amp;amp; flikr, your RSS Feed. Noticeably missing here are are updates from Facebook and Myspace...I think some people are using those services, right?.&amp;nbsp; Others that might be interesting...to see as web activities they might think to add in the future would be thinks like what items you have dugg via Digg.com?&amp;nbsp; The list could go on and on.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;img style="border-bottom:0px;border-left:0px;border-top:0px;border-right:0px;" border="0" alt="Home-2" src="http://windowsconnected.com/cfs-file.ashx/__key/CommunityServer.Blogs.Components.WeblogFiles/joshs_5F00_blog/Home_2D00_2_5F00_3.png" width="485" height="297" /&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Besides the relative instability of Home.live.com over the last few days, which I hope is related to me using IE8 and the fact that they are probably having some load problems, is that fact that the portal isn&amp;#39;t all that customizable.&amp;nbsp; Here is a look at the customization currently possible.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;img style="border-bottom:0px;border-left:0px;border-top:0px;border-right:0px;" border="0" alt="Home-3" src="http://windowsconnected.com/cfs-file.ashx/__key/CommunityServer.Blogs.Components.WeblogFiles/joshs_5F00_blog/Home_2D00_3_5F00_3.png" width="502" height="379" /&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There isn&amp;#39;t a lot you can do.&amp;nbsp; I can&amp;#39;t seem to find a way to remove the unwanted feeds like MSN, Office Live workspaces, etc.&amp;nbsp; Nor can I find a way to add in feeds of my own choosing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Have you played with home.live.com yet? If so what are your thoughts?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;img src="http://windowsconnected.com/aggbug.aspx?PostID=27825" width="1" height="1"&gt;</description><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/Windows+Live/default.aspx">Windows Live</category><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/windows+live+wave+3/default.aspx">windows live wave 3</category><category domain="http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/tags/live+home/default.aspx">live home</category></item><item><title>WindowsConnected HP Magic Giveaway Now Closed</title><link>http://windowsconnected.com/blogs/joshs_blog/archive/2008/12/04/windowsconnected-hp-magic-giveaway-now-closed.aspx</link><pubDate>Thu, 04 Dec 2008 14:02:10 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">6a8e43d9-c7d6-4571-afe6-bea9fc913020:27811</guid><dc:creator>Josh Phillips</dc:creator><slash:comments>10</slash:comments><description>&lt;p&gt;The entry period for the WindowsConnected HP Magic Giveaway is now closed. Thank you to everyone who has entered. It has been amazing to read all of the wonderful entries. There are so many worthy causes and we wish we could award something to everyone.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We will be reviewing the entries today and will announce a winner by tomorrow.&amp;nbsp; So while you wait for who our winner is you can visit all of the currently running contests to increase your chances of winning something in this amazing opportunity:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;table class="style6" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"&gt;  &lt;tr style="height:15pt;"&gt; &lt;td style="border-bottom-color:#f0f0f0;border-left:windowtext 0.5pt solid;background-color:#eeece1;border-top-color:#f0f0f0;width:118pt;height:15pt;border-right:windowtext 0.5pt solid;" class="xl73"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:x-small;"&gt;&lt;a href="http://morningsidemom.wordpress.com/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;font 